        <section class="article-information-group toggle-content is-visible" id="article-information">

			
							<section class="article-information abstract">
					<h2>Abstract</h2>
					We study the response of international investment flows to short- and long-run growth news. Among developed G7 countries, positive long-run news for domestic productivity induces a net outflow of investments, in contrast to the effects of short-run growth shocks. We document that a standard Backus, Keho, and Kydland (1994) (BKK) model fails to reproduce this novel empirical evidence. We augment this model with Epstein and Zin (1989) preferences (EZ-BKK) and characterize the resulting recursive risk-sharing scheme. The response of international capital flows in the EZ-BKK model is consistent with the data.				</section>
			
							<section class="article-information citation">
					<h2>Citation</h2>
